nodes.bodyText:
@violetagg you are right that when the major/minor and micro version matches in OSGi the qualifier is then compared lexicographically. Also a version without a qualifier is always ranked lower than a version with a qualifier e.g. 3.4.1 will be lower than 3.4.1.RELEASE.
So with all the examples we get following order:

3.4.1 (lowest)
3.4.1.202011251350
3.4.1.BUILD-202011251350
3.4.1.RELEASE (highest)

Thats the version compareTo method of bnd:
public int compareTo(Version other) {
	if (other == this)
		return 0;

	Version o = other;
	int cmp = major - o.major;
	if (cmp != 0)
		return cmp;

	cmp = minor - o.minor;
	if (cmp != 0)
		return cmp;

	cmp = micro - o.micro;
	if (cmp != 0)
		return cmp;

	if (qualifier != null)
		cmp = 1;
	if (o.qualifier != null)
		cmp += 2;

	switch (cmp) {
		case 0 :
			return 0;
		case 1 :
			return 1;
		case 2 :
			return -1;
	}
	return qualifier.compareTo(o.qualifier);
}
There are probably more ways to solve this but I also agree that using a timestamp for snapshots would be better.

